The patch has functional issues in the new timestamp normalization and TypeScript projection configuration boundary. Both can accept malformed caller input silently instead of preserving the documented hard-reject behavior.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Reject invalid calendar dates before normalizing timestamps — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1861-1864
  For BYO-LLM edge timestamps with a shape-valid but impossible date such as `2025-02-30T00:00:00Z` or `2025-04-31T00:00:00Z`, SQLite's `strftime('%s', ?)` normalizes the value to a later real date instead of returning NULL. That bypasses the new hard-reject contract and stores a different instant than the provider supplied, so invalidated/valid edges can be shifted silently; add an explicit calendar round-trip or range check before accepting the epoch.

- [P2] Validate projection spec strings before native call — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/ts/src/index.ts:791-793
  When a JS caller passes a projection `name`, role, tokenizer/embedder, or `drop` entry containing a lone UTF-16 surrogate, napi-rs converts it to U+FFFD before the Rust-side guard runs, unlike the other TS entry points that call `validateFfiString` first. This lets malformed FFI strings be persisted under a different projection name/value instead of raising `WriteValidationError`; validate the spec/drop string tree in the TS wrapper before invoking native.
